No, Riggors, you have severely misinterpreted me.  My post is only about the original thread topic which stated that deleting posts within threads might be a good idea.  Let me state:<br>
<br>
+ I am FOR having many forums<br>
+ I am FOR having threads moved to the correct forum<br>
+ I am FOR deleting _THREADS_ that are totally off topic from the start (e.g. porn, discussion of auto maintenance, etc)<br>
<br>
- I am AGAINST deleting _POSTS_ in threads that are not directly related to the original thread's topic. &lt;-- This is the point I made in my post.  My preference is that once a thread has been started in the correct forum, nobody's posts should be modified in it. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ujcasetn.showPublicProfile?language=EN>jcasetn</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 73<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(3/20/02 5:26:50 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fpaladinsofnorrathgeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=14909.topic&index=28>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Highjacking Thread Proposal...Opinions?</span><hr size=1> While I realize that some topics might be more appropriate to high level players than low level players I think this segmentation has hurt more than it has helped and was done to appease a small, but vocal number of whiney high level players.  <br>
<br>
So now they have their own forum.  Fine let them post it in it if they want.  But for me, if I post something with regards to a quest or high level ability, perhaps I want feedback from as many different perspectives as possible, not just the crotchety elite (so called).  <br>
<br>
Maybe someone who isn't doing quests currently but has done the quest in the past might have something to contribute, but because they're not doing the quest thing currently they don't ever look at those boards.  <br>
<br>
To have a forum devoted solely to quests is a bit of a bad idea anyway.  Why?  Because people are looking for specific information, and ussually not discussion.  So once they get their info, bang, they leave the forum.  Therefore, most of the contributors to such an area would only be others who are doing some other quest but just may happen to catch sight of your post and reply to it.  <br>
<br>
I posted with regards to the Divine Might quest.  I *specifically* didn't post in the quest forum because in actuality, my quesiton had practically nothing to do with the quest.  It's not like I was asking which faction to raise or which NPC to talk to next.  It was really to get some ideas on how to engage phinny and the seahorses.  I could have posted the exact same thing but just said &quot;my guild is doing a raid there for swirlspine belts, what do you think?&quot;  Now my post has been moved to the quests forum and the various and diverse opinions I hoped to get, I never got them.  Just one example of how well-meaned moderation is usually a mistake.  From now on I guess I should simply post all my quest related questions in the general forum but casually leave out the word 'quest' in the post.  I won't mention that I want a book of scale, just &quot;how do I kill nagafen or vox?&quot;<br>
<br>
My point is that the board is losing some of its quality because the discussion is being over-regulated.  An open forum is just that - open.  When a moderator runs into the room waving his arms the moment the topic digresses a bit and announces &quot;okay okay all of you that want to keep talking about this, off to the warwall, sorry, gotta keep things nice and tidy&quot; then the free flow of ideas is gone.  It is the main reason for Free Speach (in the US anyway), because moderation, well-meaned or not, is very dangerous and inhibits the free flow of ideas.<br>
<br>
<br>
